{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512054"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11836"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11836"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.19,0.01,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92385"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1351"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35918"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 24-year-old man presents with a 2-day history of a sore throat and runny nose. He also has a non-productive cough and feels tired and generally unwell. He has not experienced any fevers or chills. He is a non-smoker, does not take any medications and has no allergies. He teaches at a primary school and comments that several of the children have had similar symptoms recently. He is fully vaccinated for Covid-19 and recent testing for SARS-CoV-2 was negative. On examination his blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Oropharyngeal examination shows erythema posteriorly with tonsillar enlargement, but no exudate. The anterior cervical nodes are tender to palpation, but are not enlarged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Symptomatic treatment only","Throat swab for potential streptococcal infection","Streptococcal antibody assay","Benzylpenicillin","Azithromycin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EViral pharyngitis is the most common cause of sore throat in patients of all ages. The management of viral pharyngitis is \u003Cstrong\u003Esymptomatic treatment. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EAntibiotics are reserved for cases of bacterial infection with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E being first line for Streptococcus B infection, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eazithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E being used for mycoplasma infections. It is important to note that most cases of bacterial pharyngitis and tonsillitis may be self-limiting even without the use of antibiotics. However, antibiotics for suspected bacterial infections should be administered early for those who are severely unwell or who are at high risk of acute rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Centor criteria can be used to determine the likelihood that pharyngitis or tonsillitis is caused by streptococcal bacteria. According to this criteria, streptococcal infection is more likely when there is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etender cervical lymphadenopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etonsillar exudate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efever above 38 degrees\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eage 3-14\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ean absence of cough\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this patient is an adult and has both a cough and rhinorrhoea, with no tonsillar exudate and a temperature below 38 degrees, a viral cause is more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethroat swab for potential streptococcal infection\u003C/strong\u003E could be done if the symptoms worsen or fail to resolve, or if there was a high suspicion of bacterial tonsillitis.  For this patient, he would have a Centor score of 2, which makes it less likely to have a bacterial tonsillitis and would have less gain for performing the test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E A \u003Cstrong\u003Estreptococcal antibody assay\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case and is more commonly ordered for investigation of complications stemming from a previous streptococcal A infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Viral pharyngitis is the most common cause of sore throat in all age groups, and is best managed symptomatically.","Bacterial pharyngitis does not always require antibiotic therapy, but should be prescribed early where the risk of acute rheumatic fever is high."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Limited Sore Throat.. In:\u202fTherapeutic Guidelines: Antibiotic [Internet]. Topic under revision, amended in March\u202f2025 [cited\u202f2025\u202fJul\u202f27]. Available from: https://app.tg.org.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=bartonella-infections\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_ABG_Sore_throat_topic_11#c_ABG_Sore_throat_topic_11","Muthanna A et al. Diagnostic Accuracy of Centor Score for Diagnosis of Group A Streptococcal Pharyngitis among Adults in Primary Care Clinics in Malaysia. Malaysia Journal of Medical Science. 2022.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9438850/","Wolford RW, Goyal A, Belgam Syed SY, et al. Pharyngitis. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519550/","https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32273409/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92385"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11836"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92385"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T08:11:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T08:12:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r